dinary people whose lives were never recorded in history books. Focusing primarily on these unknown citizens-an accountant in the first Treasury Department, a coachmaker whose clients were politicians doing business at the State House, an African American founder of St. Thomas’s African Episcopal Church, and others-Yamin presents a colorful portrait of old Philadelphia. She also discusses political aspects of archaeology today-who supports particular projects and why, and what has been lost to bulldozers and heedlessness. Digging in the City of Brotherly Love tells the exhilarating story of doing archaeology in the real world and using its findings to understand the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchaeologistszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aArchaeology and historyzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aHistoric siteszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aUrban archaeologyzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030010091440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014264840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300142648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300142648/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY